## Additional Design Considerations

**Tenant-Scoped Partitioning**: Use tenantId as the first partition key with date-based sort keys (e.g., `tenantId#2026-04-12`). This ensures events from the same tenant are co-located for efficient reads while enabling date-range queries and compliance exports.

**Late Data Handling**: Configure Kinesis stream retention to 7 days. Lambda consumers checkpoint sequence numbers per shard. Use a separate dead-letter queue (DLQ) in S3 for events arriving after checkpoint gaps, reprocessed via a scheduled backfill Lambda.

**Immutable Audit Logs**: Write all ingested events to S3 with Object Lock (Compliance mode) preventing deletion for 30 days. Enable S3 Versioning and replicate via Cross-Region Replication (CRR) to a secondary audit bucket.

**Per-Tenant Quotas**: DynamoDB tracks per-tenant event counts with a quota table. Conditional writes reject events exceeding limits, emitting CloudWatch metrics for alerting.

**Failover/Backfill Plan**: On region failure, promote secondary Kinesis stream via Route53 health checks. A backfill Lambda replays from the S3 DLQ with timestamps preserved, deduplicating against the existing DynamoDB table. After 30 days, S3 Lifecycle rules transition audit logs to Glacier and expire objects via Object Expiration.

